# Three.js Rules

## Scene Setup

- Always create the three core objects before anything else: **Scene**, **Camera**, and **WebGLRenderer**.
- Use `PerspectiveCamera(fov, aspect, near, far)`; set `near` as large as possible and `far` as small as possible to maximise depth-buffer precision.
- Update the camera aspect ratio and call `camera.updateProjectionMatrix()` whenever the window is resized.
- Attach the renderer's `domElement` (canvas) to the DOM and resize the renderer with `renderer.setSize(width, height)`.
- Call `renderer.setPixelRatio(Math.min(window.devicePixelRatio, 2))` to balance sharpness and performance.

## Animation Loop

- Use `renderer.setAnimationLoop(callback)` (or `requestAnimationFrame`) for the render loop — never use `setInterval`.
- Keep the animation callback pure: update object state, then call `renderer.render(scene, camera)`.
- Use a **Clock** (`THREE.Clock`) for time-based animations instead of relying on frame count.

```js
const clock = new THREE.Clock();

renderer.setAnimationLoop(() => {
  const delta = clock.getDelta();
  // update objects using delta
  renderer.render(scene, camera);
});
```

## Geometries & Materials

- Reuse geometries and materials across multiple meshes — creating them per-instance wastes memory.
- Dispose of geometries (`geometry.dispose()`) and materials (`material.dispose()`) when they are no longer needed.
- Use `BufferGeometry` directly; the legacy `Geometry` class was removed in Three.js r125.
- Prefer **MeshStandardMaterial** or **MeshPhysicalMaterial** for PBR shading; use **MeshBasicMaterial** only for unlit objects.
- Set `material.side = THREE.FrontSide` (default) unless double-sided rendering is explicitly needed.

## Lighting

- Add at least an `AmbientLight` for base illumination and a directional or point light for shadows.
- Enable shadows selectively: `renderer.shadowMap.enabled = true`, then set `castShadow` and `receiveShadow` only on meshes that need them.
- Use `renderer.shadowMap.type = THREE.PCFSoftShadowMap` for soft shadow edges.

## Textures & Loaders

- Use `TextureLoader` (or `GLTFLoader`, `DRACOLoader`, etc.) and handle the loading lifecycle with callbacks or Promises.
- Always call `texture.dispose()` when a texture is no longer in use.
- Set `texture.colorSpace = THREE.SRGBColorSpace` for colour textures; leave it as `LinearSRGBColorSpace` for normal/roughness maps.
- Use a single shared `LoadingManager` to track global loading progress.

## 3D Models

- Prefer **GLTF/GLB** format for models — it is the standard format recommended by Three.js.
- Use `DRACOLoader` for compressed GLTF meshes to reduce file size.
- Traverse loaded scenes with `object.traverse()` to configure shadows or swap materials.

## Performance

- Minimise draw calls by merging static geometries with `BufferGeometryUtils.mergeGeometries`.
- Use `InstancedMesh` for large numbers of identical objects.
- Cull objects that are off-screen: enable `object.frustumCulled = true` (default).
- Use `renderer.info` to monitor draw calls, triangles, and textures during development.
- Avoid creating new `Vector3`, `Quaternion`, or `Matrix4` objects inside the render loop — reuse instances.

## Resource Cleanup

- When tearing down a Three.js scene (e.g., component unmount in React), stop the animation loop, dispose all geometries/materials/textures, and call `renderer.dispose()`.

```js
function cleanup() {
  renderer.setAnimationLoop(null);
  scene.traverse((object) => {
    if (object.geometry) object.geometry.dispose();
    if (object.material) {
      const mats = Array.isArray(object.material) ? object.material : [object.material];
      mats.forEach((m) => m.dispose());
    }
  });
  renderer.dispose();
}
```

## Integration with React (React Three Fiber)

- Prefer **React Three Fiber (R3F)** when building Three.js scenes inside React apps — it handles the render loop and cleanup automatically.
- Use **@react-three/drei** for common helpers (OrbitControls, Environment, Text, etc.).
- Use **@react-three/postprocessing** for post-processing effects.

## Controls

- Use `OrbitControls` from `three/examples/jsm/controls/OrbitControls.js` for camera interaction.
- Always call `controls.update()` inside the animation loop when `enableDamping` is `true`.
